observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that the: 

Municipal Budget Officer ensure that any changes made in the LDRRMFIP be communicated to the MDRRM Officer and Acting Municipal Accountant; 

MDRRM Officer evaluate the PPAs in the continuing appropriation and special trust fund and make appropriate actions thereto in order that the MDRRM Fund be utilized; 

MDRRMO, Municipal Engineer and BAC Chairperson monitor and facilitate the implementation of the PPAs under the MDRRM Fund by monitoring the period of its implementation. Henceforth, ensure that all projects appropriated in MDRRM Fund be implemented during the year for which it was appropriated; 

Acting Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer revert to the surplus of General Fund the unutilized balances of LDRRMF held in Trust Fund for more than five (5) years to make it available for appropriation for social services pursuant to Item 5.1.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; and

MDRRMO, Municipal Budget Officer and Acting Municipal Accountant provide acceptable justification on the observations noted regarding the appropriation and utilization of LDRRM Fund

We recommended and Management agreed that the GAD Focal Person:

Ensure compliance with the observation of DILG-Provincial Office on their review of the GPB of the MGB in order to obtain certificate of endorsement;

Prioritize the attendance of the GFPS Executive Committee, TWG and MET to various GAD-related trainings and seminars in order for them to serve as a catalyst in gender mainstreaming in the Municipality and identify gender issues in their GAD Plan and Budget;

Instruct the MPDC to maintain database with sex-disaggregated data and other relevant data that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation, and aid in identifying gender issues;

Instruct the GFPS to prioritize identifying gender issue that is focus on the need of the clients; and

Instruct the GFPS-TWG to submit the DILG-received GAD Accomplishment Report and its supporting documents to facilitate evaluation of the success of the GPB for CY 2019.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:

Municipal Accountant and General Service Officer coordinate with each other and prepare supporting schedules to facilitate the proper reconciliation of the property accounts and establishment of actual existence, ownership, and condition of the properties; 

Municipal Accountant (i) analyze the nature of the transactions of the semi-expendable supplies and property, misclassified accounts, CIP account in the Trust Fund and make an appropriate adjustment therein; and (ii) transfer the completed asset from Trust Fund to General Fund and provide depreciation;

General Service Officer (i) remove the expendable and semi-expendable properties from the RPCPPE; (ii) account all determined unserviceable properties to facilitate the preparation of IIRUP and other required supporting documents for disposal; (iii) prepare and maintain RLRN and Road Map to account for the Local Roads and reconcile with the Registry of Public Infrastructures maintained by the Accounting Office; and (iv) exert efforts to have the pieces of land owned by the Municipal Government titled in its name;

Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count and technical valuation of the local road network to determine the current value of the road components to facilitate the preparation of the RPCLRN; and 

Municipal Engineer maintain road map and provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Service Officer with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended that the:

BAC Secretariat ensure that the NOA and NTP are posted in the PhilGEPS within the set timeframe;

BAC Chairperson ensure that the winning suppliers has the capability to deliver the requested supplies and materials on which the terms the contract are called for to avoid issuance of amendment orders or extension of contract time;

OIC-Municipal Engineer (i) compute the liquidated damages incurred for the delay in the implementation of Construction of Drainage Canal at BBII (BBCS) and demand for payment from the contractor; (ii) ensure that the variation orders shall be duly supported with the required document as per by Item 1.5.a of Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and (iii) see to it that the infrastructure projects be implemented within the contract period and consider computation of liquidated damages whenever the projects were not completed as per contract; 

Municipal Accountant demand for payment of the liquidated damages of ₱240,868.68 the delay in the delivery of the noted projects; and

Municipal Accountant, BAC Chairperson and Secretariat, OIC-Municipal Engineer and concerned employees submit justification of the observations noted above, and the lacking supporting documents.

We recommended that the: 

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) (i) ensure that NOA and NTP are posted in the PhilGEPS within the set timeframe; (ii) observe the timeline in the conduct of post qualification process, execution of contract agreement, issuance of NTP and project implementation period; (iii) see to it that bidding documents are properly dated in order to verify the validity and propriety of each of the documents submitted by the prospective bidder; and (iv) consider the provisions of Annex D and Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 relative to the grant and issuance of suspension of work for both goods and infrastructure projects;

Municipal Engineer (i) compute the applicable liquidated damages for the delayed delivery of materials and implementation of infrastructure projects; (ii) submit acceptable justification on the observations noted in the excessive claim of labor payroll for the Construction of Evacuation Center at Barangays Carmundo, Tawas and Anilao; (iii) immediately process the payment of labor payroll for the Construction of Evacuation Center at Barangays Orconuma and Batangan; and (iv) ensure that the projects downloaded by the NGAs are implemented as planned to avoid withdrawal of the projects by the source agencies;    

Acting Municipal Accountant (i) recognize in the appropriate asset accounts the facilities constructed as per COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015; and (ii) review the computation of liquidated damages in the procurement of materials for the construction of evacuation centers; and

Municipal Accountant, BAC, Municipal Engineer and concerned employees submit the lacking supporting documents.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor: 

Recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan to (i) adopt the SWM plan in compliance with the NSWMC Resolution No. 1168 series of 2018 dated December 6, 2018; and (ii) prioritize the enactment of the “no segregation, no collection” ordinance, among others, as embodied in the request of the MENRO dated January 20, 2020; 

Instruct the MENRO to (i) disseminate information education campaign materials regarding the segregation of waste at source; (ii) ensure that the operation of the open dumpsite is properly controlled and complied in accordance with Rule XIII- Operation of Controlled Dumpsite of the IRR of RA No. 9003, (iii) fast track the negotiation for the procurement of land in Brgy. Hagupit for the implementation of full closure of dumpsite in Brgy. Sagana; and (iv) ensure that all procured SWM equipment were operational to aid in the achievement of the goals of RA No. 9003; 

Instruct the Local Finance Committee, through the Municipal Budget Officer, to appropriate funds for the projects identified in the 10-year SWMP of the Municipality for the full realization of the goals of RA No. 9003; and

Through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and establishment of material recovery facilities.

